@John_Waters yes, and my point was that it should switch off of the keyboard when it has stopped presenting text for a future input, not when it has been triggered to adjust the screen with hotkeys and sees text change each time it happens.

You're saying that when the proposal stops changing, it may stay on the flow area for a split-second.

The flow area for on efficiency is already set to a sensitive threshold (25% for the segment example).

If after the split-second and at least x% of position-offset-with-submission still lays off of the flow:
a) Call if it was above (if it didn't require steal visible land), if it was below (that would be new land that needs to be usurped), or count it as a draw.
b) If the above did not constitute enough land to meet the minimum required to steal from the black rose in the default example, delegate it to that block (black rose) directly (I don't think pragmatic implementations of the mechanize proposal format were implemented with this corner-case in mind, and thus don't allow for the import of the position offset)

What is the purpose of the flow area then? To have line breaks?

The purpose of the flow-area isn't to get line-breaks per se--it is to regulate the amount of "position offset".

The simplest way to explain to someone who doesn't think in web terms is: The flow-area is a way of inputting html code into the mech evaluation system, so that the devs don't have to segregate text inputs from code when asking testers what they see in the system. "The system is broken! Where's 'subtrees', we're not seeing 'subtrees'!" OK, let's use the disagreement color to make it obvious that you didn't use the flow-area format correctly (by default, you don't use a symbol within the text area to indicate 'subtrees'). "Utypeon don't you get it, we were asking for the disagreement colour" insert programmer-level eye-rolls. Disregarding how this makes the game more clumsy to talk about (temporarily), the flow-area is also intentionally burdened with a myriad of limitations so that the code doesn't think it's a text area, so that artists aren't constantly debugging or running ui tests against the mech when implementing~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~-~, so3', '

In the decision making module, the reputation agent modifies the action-taking module's comprehension of its own decisions.

### Improving your reputation

In training, the reputation agent's decision was totaled with all other human agent's decisions, and a Reputation shared among humans was calculated and submitted as a vector c to each action. The shape of c is previously calculated to match the acting parameters supplied to the action-taking module.

At runtime, the reputation will be recalculated each time it is needed rather than on each action. At first the reputation will be undefined, but is updated slowly as decisions are learned. This could mean it is more accurate in the later stages of your earlier investments.

### Personal Reputation v. Shared Reputation

In general it is in your best interest to control your own reputation, as that is what is used to reward you and other agents in the system. It is possible you will wish to manipulate your behavior up to and including lying to the modules to mislead them into thinking you had a better reputation.

However, be warned - your behavior will be left to its own devices if you perform inefficiently, saving the decision-making module's time and therefore the betterment of future agents. The behavior of high reputation agents will be researched to steal their winning techniques and improve them and push them out to the world for the greater good -- in other words a success of any known technique would lower the reputation of the technique's users rather than improve it. Low-status actors will be studied for what is causing their poor decisions, and low-status technology will be adopted to increase understanding.

Successful behavior won't be made available to the public at all if this would cause a statistical contradiction for the system. This can be further explained later in the training on how randomness can affect statistics. Being too statistically precise can be more damaging to an agent than being slightly less.
